# List all files in given COS directory
def list_blobs(bucket_name, folder_name):
    gcs_client = storage.Client()
    bucket = gcs_client.bucket(bucket_name)
    blobs = list(bucket.list_blobs(prefix=folder_name))

    for blob in blobs:
        print(blob.name + '\t' + str(blob.size))
In [6]:
# List all files in given COS directory
def list_blobs_pd(bucket_name, folder_name):
    gcs_client = storage.Client()
    bucket = gcs_client.bucket(bucket_name)
    blobs = list(bucket.list_blobs(prefix=folder_name))

    blob_name = []
    blob_size = []
    
    for blob in blobs:
        blob_name.append(blob.name)
        blob_size.append(blob.size)

    blobs_df = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(blob_name, blob_size)), columns=['Name','Size'])

    blobs_df.style.format({"Size": "{:,.0f}"}) 
    
    return blobs_df
In [7]:
# Delete folder from COS bucket
def delete_folder(bucket_name, folder_name):
    gcs_client = storage.Client()
    bucket = gcs_client.bucket(bucket_name)
    blobs = list(bucket.list_blobs(prefix=folder_name))

    for blob in blobs:
        blob.delete()

Read Amazon product reviews Data¶

You have ~150M Amazon product reviews loaded into GCS bucket "gs://msca-bdp-amazon/amazon_reviews/".
Your task is to identify:

  1. Which product category gets most reviews
  2. Which product category gets highest / lowest review star ratings
  3. Do you see seasonality in reviews?
  • Is every product category getting consistent number of reviews throughout the year?
  • Any product categories that are getting more reviews during certain times of the year? If yes, which product categories and what times of the year?
  1. Which reviews are getting the most helpful votes / total votes?
  • Any correlation between the length of review headline / review body (in number words) and the "helpfulness" of the review?
  • Do you see any correlation between how many reviews a certain customer (customer_id) published and the "helpfulness" of the reviews?
  1. Ensure your jobs are executed in the most computationally effective way. Use comments in the notebook to explain how you accomplish this computational effectiveness based on your knowledge of Spark

1. Which product category gets most reviews¶

## Select only the 'product_category' column instead of bringing the whole dataframe to be more efficient
review_df.select('product_category').\
groupby('product_category').\
agg(count('*').alias('review_count')).\
orderBy('review_count', ascending=False).limit(5).show()

3. Do you see seasonality in reviews?¶

  • Is every product category getting consistent number of reviews throughout the year?

Not every product category gets the consistent number of reviews throughout the year, as we can see in the above plots. Similarly, there is a extremely low correlation (-0.0002) between how many reviews a certain customer published and the "helpfulness" of the reviews. On contrary, if we change the definition of the helpfulness from "the average of helpful_votes per customer" to "the total of helpful_votes per customer", it will show a rather high (0.65) correlation simply because the more reviews a customer left, the higher exposure he/she would get, however, that doesn't mean on average this customer's review is more helpful.
